```javascript
const cards = document.querySelectorAll(".card");

cards.forEach(card => {
    card.classList.add("highlighted");
});
```

`querySelectorAll(".card")` returns a **NodeList** of all matching elements. The `forEach` method iterates through each card, and `classList.add("highlighted")` adds the CSS class. The corresponding `.highlighted` styles would be defined in CSS, maintaining separation of concerns.

This pattern means JavaScript only **adds or removes CSS classes** on elements, while **all visual styling is defined in CSS**. JavaScript never directly sets `style.backgroundColor` or other visual properties.

**Why it's best practice:**
1. **Separation of concerns** — styling stays in CSS, behavior in JS
2. **Easier maintenance** — change colors/animations in CSS without touching JS
3. **CSS transitions work** — class-based changes automatically animate with CSS transitions
4. **Reusability** — the same class can be applied to any element
5. **Performance** — browsers optimize class-based changes better than inline styles

**Example:**
```css
/* CSS handles ALL visual changes */
.faq-answer { max-height: 0; overflow: hidden; transition: max-height 0.4s ease; }
.faq-item.active .faq-answer { max-height: 300px; }
```
```javascript
// JavaScript ONLY toggles the class
faqItem.classList.toggle("active");
// CSS handles the smooth animation automatically!
```
JavaScript does the minimum work (toggling a class), while CSS does the heavy lifting (animations, colors, layout changes).
